{"title_page": "Geranium viscosissimum", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Geraniumviscosissimum.jpg\n|genus = Geranium\n|species = viscosissimum\n|authority = [[Friedrich Ernst Ludwig von Fischer|Fisch.]] & C.A. Mey. ex C.A. Mey.\n|synonyms = ''Geranium attenuilobum'' <small>G.N. & F.F. Jones</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Geranium viscosissimum''''', commonly known as the '''sticky purple geranium''', is a [[Perennial plant|perennial]] in the flowering plant family [[Geraniaceae]].<ref>[http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=GEVIV USDA Plants Database]</ref> It is thought to be a [[protocarnivorous plant]].\n\n==Distribution==\nThis [[herbaceous perennial]] plant is native to the [[Northwestern United States]], [[California]], and [[Nevada]], including in the [[Great Basin]] and [[Rocky Mountains]] regions; and to [[Western Canada]], including in the [[Canadian Rockies]].\n\nHabitats it is found in include [[yellow pine forest]], northern [[juniper]] woodland, lowland to higher elevation [[meadow]]s, and [[wetland]]-[[riparian zone]]s;  from {{convert|1000|-|2500|m|ft}} in elevation.\n\n==Description==\n''Geranium viscosissimum'' is a large, clumped {{convert|0.5|-|3|ft|m}} tall perennial wild geranium.  The stem, leaves, and flower stalks are covered with sticky hairs.  The right-green leaves are dissected, many-toothed, and deeply-lobed.\n\nIts bloom period is April to September, depending on elevation and latitude. It has {{convert|1.5|in|cm}} saucer-shaped pink flowers with reddish-purple lines on the petals. They occur in an open cluster near the top of strong, branching {{convert|1|-|2|ft|m}} flower stalks.\n\n===Carnivorous syndrome===\nIn his 1999 journal article, G.G. Spomer tested several plants in the [[Pacific Northwest]] for the [[carnivorous plant|carnivorous]] syndrome, using the digestion of proteins as the diagnostic tool to determine which plants appeared to produce [[protease]] enzymes capable of breaking down potential prey. ''Geranium viscosissimum'' displayed a capability to digest and absorb the <sup>14</sup>C-labeled algal protein placed on the sticky trichomes that the plant possesses. However, it is not known whether the digestive enzymes were produced by the plant itself or surface microbes.<ref>Spomer, G.G. (1999). Evidence of protocarnivorous capabilities in ''Geranium viscosissimum'' and ''Potentilla arguta'' and other sticky plants. ''International Journal of Plant Sciences'', 160(1): 98-101.</ref> Additionally, some definitions of carnivory require the plant to gain some tangible benefit in capturing and digesting prey, such as increased seed yield or growth. Such an experiment has not been done with this species.\n\n==Uses==\nThe flowers and leaves of this species are edible, but reported to be astringent.  Flowers can be added to salads or used as a garnish.<ref>[http://www.pfaf.org/User/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Geranium+viscosissimum PFAF.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref>\n\n===Medicinal===\nBlackfeet Indians used an infusion from this plant to treat diarrhea and gastric upset and urinary irritations.  The root of this plant is astringent and was dried and powdered and used by Native Americans to stop external bleeding.<ref>[http://naeb.brit.org/uses/search/?string=Geranium+viscosissimum  Native American Ethnobotany Database.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref><ref>Edible and Medicinal Plants of the West, Gregory L. Tilford, {{ISBN|0-87842-359-1}}</ref>\n\n===Cultivation===\n''Geranium viscosissimum'' is cultivated as an [[ornamental plant]] by specialty [[plant nursery|plant nurseries]], for use in [[native plant]] and [[wildlife garden]]s.<ref>[http://calscape.org/Geranium-viscosissimum-()  Calscape.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref><ref>[http://www.laspilitas.com/nature-of-california/plants/327--geranium-viscosissimum Las Pilitas Nursery Horticulture Database: ''Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky Geranium, Klamath Geranium)]</ref>  The plant attracts butterflies.<ref>[http://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=GEVI2  Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center Native Plant Information Network\u2212NPIN: ''Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky purple geranium, Sticky wild geranium)] \u2014 ''horticulture info''.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Potentilla arguta]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Geranium+viscosissimum Calflora Database: Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky purple geranium)]\n* [http://calphotos.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/img_query?rel-taxon=begins+with&where-taxon=Geranium+viscosissimum  UC CalPhotos gallery for ''Geranium viscosissimum'']\n\n{{CarnivorousPlants}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5549882}}\n\n[[Category:Geranium|viscosissimum]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Northwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Canada]]\n[[Category:Flora of California]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Great Basin]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Rocky Mountains]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of North America]]\n[[Category:Plants used in traditional Native American medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Geraniumviscosissimum.jpg\n|genus = Geranium\n|species = viscosissimum\n|authority = [[Friedrich Ernst Ludwig von Fischer|Fisch.]] & C.A. Mey. ex C.A. Mey.\n|synonyms = ''Geranium attenuilobum'' <small>G.N. & F.F. Jones</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Geranium viscosissimum''''', commonly known as the '''sticky purple geranium''', is a [[Perennial plant|perennial]] in the [[Geraniaceae]] family of flowering plants.<ref>[http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=GEVIV USDA Plants Database]</ref> It is thought to be a [[protocarnivorous plant]].\n\n==Distribution==\nThis [[herbaceous perennial]] plant is native to the [[Northwestern United States]], [[California]], and [[Nevada]], including in the [[Great Basin]] and [[Rocky Mountains]] regions; and to [[Western Canada]], including in the [[Canadian Rockies]].\n\nHabitats it is found in include [[yellow pine forest]], northern [[juniper]] woodland, lowland to higher elevation [[meadow]]s, and [[wetland]]-[[riparian zone]]s;  from {{convert|1000|-|2500|m|ft}} in elevation.\n\n==Description==\n''Geranium viscosissimum'' is a large, clumped {{convert|0.5|-|3|ft|m}} tall perennial wild geranium.  The stem, leaves, and flower stalks are covered with sticky hairs.  The right-green leaves are dissected, many-toothed, and deeply-lobed.\n\nIts bloom period is April to September, depending on elevation and latitude. It has {{convert|1.5|in|cm}} saucer-shaped pink flowers with reddish-purple lines on the petals. They occur in an open cluster near the top of strong, branching {{convert|1|-|2|ft|m}} flower stalks.\n\n===Carnivorous syndrome===\nIn his 1999 journal article, G.G. Spomer tested several plants in the [[Pacific Northwest]] for the [[carnivorous plant|carnivorous]] syndrome, using the digestion of proteins as the diagnostic tool to determine which plants appeared to produce [[protease]] enzymes capable of breaking down potential prey. ''Geranium viscosissimum'' displayed a capability to digest and absorb the <sup>14</sup>C-labeled algal protein placed on the sticky trichomes that the plant possesses. However, it is not known whether the digestive enzymes were produced by the plant itself or surface microbes.<ref>Spomer, G.G. (1999). Evidence of protocarnivorous capabilities in ''Geranium viscosissimum'' and ''Potentilla arguta'' and other sticky plants. ''International Journal of Plant Sciences'', 160(1): 98-101.</ref> Additionally, some definitions of carnivory require the plant to gain some tangible benefit in capturing and digesting prey, such as increased seed yield or growth. Such an experiment has not been done with this species.\n\n==Uses==\nThe flowers and leaves of this species are edible, but reported to be astringent.  Flowers can be added to salads or used as a garnish.<ref>[http://www.pfaf.org/User/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Geranium+viscosissimum PFAF.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref>\n\n===Medicinal===\nBlackfeet Indians used an infusion from this plant to treat diarrhea and gastric upset and urinary irritations.  The root of this plant is astringent and was dried and powdered and used by Native Americans to stop external bleeding.<ref>[http://naeb.brit.org/uses/search/?string=Geranium+viscosissimum  Native American Ethnobotany Database.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref><ref>Edible and Medicinal Plants of the West, Gregory L. Tilford, {{ISBN|0-87842-359-1}}</ref>\n\n===Cultivation===\n''Geranium viscosissimum'' is cultivated as an [[ornamental plant]] by specialty [[plant nursery|plant nurseries]], for use in [[native plant]] and [[wildlife garden]]s.<ref>[http://calscape.org/Geranium-viscosissimum-()  Calscape.org: ''Geranium viscosissimum'']</ref><ref>[http://www.laspilitas.com/nature-of-california/plants/327--geranium-viscosissimum Las Pilitas Nursery Horticulture Database: ''Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky Geranium, Klamath Geranium)]</ref>  The plant attracts butterflies.<ref>[http://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=GEVI2  Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center Native Plant Information Network\u2212NPIN: ''Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky purple geranium, Sticky wild geranium)] \u2014 ''horticulture info''.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Potentilla arguta]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Geranium+viscosissimum Calflora Database: Geranium viscosissimum'' (Sticky purple geranium)]\n* [http://calphotos.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/img_query?rel-taxon=begins+with&where-taxon=Geranium+viscosissimum  UC CalPhotos gallery for ''Geranium viscosissimum'']\n\n{{CarnivorousPlants}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5549882}}\n\n[[Category:Geranium|viscosissimum]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Northwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Canada]]\n[[Category:Flora of California]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Flora of t